The Jewish Question is a serious issue which deserves to be addressed in the public discourse. Unfortunately, many treat awareness of it as an anti-social subculture through which they can signify how edgy they are.

About a month ago, I said that it was useful for us that Ye brought up Jewish influence in the media because it was an opportunity to broaden the discussion of the issue. But I stressed that he is not someone who shares the same political goals as us and that he is primarily doing it because he loves controversy.

A low-IQ Black rapper going on Alex Jones while wearing a sock over his head and calling himself a Nazi isn't a threat to Jewish power. It's just a clown show.

It's common for Jewish writers to put over-the-top and ridiculous anti-semitic characters into films or TV shows as a way of discrediting anyone who addresses the Jewish Question. Think of Eric Cartman or Borat. That's how the InfoWars interview will come across to 95% of people.

Furthermore, "naming them" does not mean that you actually understand power.  Burning a Twitter account with over 30 million followers for the LOLs is not a route to power. (It wasn't "naming them" that got Ye banned. He was unbanned after Musk took over Twitter. It was the InfoWars interview.)

Is Ye going to discuss Boasian anthropology, the Frankfurt School, or the Jewish role in mass immigration? No, he's going to compare himself to Hitler and draw a Swastika in the Star of David.

I ask that people who are sincere about White advocacy treat issues like the Jewish Question with the seriousness they deserve. Seeing as Ye is a Black rapper, thankfully he isn't someone the public will naturally associate with White advocacy. But I wish those who are associated with it wouldn't get caught up in the clown show.
